## Implementation Plan

### Problem
PR #338 added consola-based logging with --verbose, --log-level flags
and SENTRY_LOG_LEVEL env var. All three had bugs:

1. --verbose was pre-parsed from argv but left in place for the api command.
   Stricli is strict — it rejects any unknown flag. Every command except api
   (which defines its own --verbose) errored.

2. --log-level=value (equals form) was not handled by extractLogLevelFromArgs
   which only checked argv.indexOf("--log-level") (exact match).

3. SENTRY_LOG_LEVEL env var worked (getEnvLogLevel returned correct level)
   but had no visible effect because all debug logging uses scoped loggers
   created by logger.withTag() at module load time. Consola withTag() creates
   completely independent instances that snapshot the parent level at creation
   time — they never see later setLogLevel() calls.

### Approach: Stricli-native flags, not argv pre-parsing

Stricli does not support global flags (bloomberg/stricli#106, closed as
not planned). The alternative used in this codebase (e.g. LIST_JSON_FLAG,
LIST_CURSOR_FLAG) is shared flag constant objects spread into each command.

buildSentryCommand() in src/lib/command.ts wraps Stricli buildCommand to:
1. Merge hidden --log-level (enum) and --verbose (boolean) into parameters
2. Wrap func to intercept, apply via setLogLevel(), and strip before calling
   the original function
3. Delegate to buildCommand for telemetry wrapping

The api command uses buildCommand directly (not buildSentryCommand) because
it has its own --verbose with HTTP semantics. It adds LOG_LEVEL_FLAG
manually and calls applyLoggingFlags() in its func.

### withTag() level propagation fix

Wrapped logger.withTag() to register all child loggers in a scopedLoggers
array. setLogLevel() iterates the array and updates each child level.

